04910nam a22007815i 9780231544344DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017058609  a97802315443447 a10.7312/sima182722doi  a(DE-B1597)500173  a(OCoLC)1019833496  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHM743.F33bS56 2018 4aHM743.F33bS56 2018 7aPHI0400002bisacsh04a302.302852231 aSimanowski, Roberto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFacebook Society :bLosing Ourselves in Sharing Ourselves /cRoberto Simanowski. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1. Stranger Friends -- t2. Automatic Autobiography -- t3. Digital Nation -- tAfterword -- tEpilogue to the English Edition -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFacebook claims that it is building a “global community.” Whether this sounds utopian, dystopian, or simply self-promotional, there is no denying that social-media platforms have altered social interaction, political life, and outlooks on the world, even for people who do not regularly use them. In this book, Roberto Simanowski takes Facebook as a starting point to investigate our social-media society—and its insidious consequences for our concept of the self.Simanowski contends that while they are often denounced as outlets for narcissism and self-branding, social networks and the practices they cultivate in fact remake the self in their image. Sharing is the outsourcing of one’s experiences, encouraging unreflective self-narration rather than conscious self-determination. Instead of experiencing the present, we are stuck ceaselessly documenting and archiving it. We let our lives become episodic autobiographies whose real author is the algorithm lurking behind the interface. As we go about accumulating more material for the platform to arrange for us, our sense of self becomes diminished—and Facebook shapes a subject who no longer minds. Social-media companies’ relentless pursuit of personal data for advertising purposes presents users with increasingly targeted, customized information, attenuating cultural memory and fracturing collective identity. Presenting a creative, philosophically informed perspective that speaks candidly to a shared reality, Facebook Society asks us to come to terms with the networked world for our own sake and for all those with whom we share it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aSocial networks. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh1 aGillespie, Susan H.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishz978311060421408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018z9783110603217oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/sima1827240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231544344/original  a978-3-11-060421-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL